---

EXECUTIVE OVERVIEW

1.0 THE NEUTRON RADIATION CHALLENGE ON MARS

Mars lacks Earth's protective magnetic field and has only 1% of Earth's atmospheric pressure. Galactic Cosmic Rays (GCRs) with energies from 10⁸ to 10²⁰ eV strike the Martian atmosphere and surface, generating complex cascades of secondary particles. The neutron component of this radiation field poses a particularly severe biological hazard due to its high Relative Biological Effectiveness (RBE) and deep tissue penetration.

Key Physics Problem: Neutron radiation on Mars exhibits a tri-modal energy distribution:

· Thermal neutrons (< 0.5 eV): Result from complete moderation in regolith
· Epithermal neutrons (0.5 eV - 0.1 MeV): Partially moderated components
· Fast neutrons (0.1 - 100+ MeV): Direct spallation products with maximum biological damage potential

The RBE for neutrons peaks in the 0.1-2 MeV range, with values up to 20-30 for certain biological endpoints, compared to 1 for gamma rays.

1.1 Mission Driver: From Science to Safety

Previous Mars radiation monitoring (MSL-RAD, Insight) served scientific discovery. Sentinel-N transforms this paradigm to active crew safety through:

· Real-time dose equivalent calculation with <10% uncertainty
· Predictive shielding adjustments 20-60 minutes before radiation events
· Infrastructure health monitoring via neutron activation analysis
· Subsurface resource prospecting via hydrogen detection

1.2 Core Design Philosophy

· Crew-Centric: Data products optimized for operational health physics
· Distributed Intelligence: Spatial resolution of 100 meters across settlement
· Fail-Operational: Triple redundancy at detector, node, and network levels
· Mars-Native: Maintenance by autonomous systems using local resources

---

MATHEMATICAL & PHYSICS FOUNDATION

2.0 NEUTRON TRANSPORT THEORY

2.1 Boltzmann Transport Equation for Martian Environment

The neutron flux distribution $\phi(\vec{r}, E, \hat{\Omega}, t)$ satisfies:

$$
\frac{1}{v}\frac{\partial\phi}{\partial t} + \hat{\Omega}\cdot\nabla\phi + \Sigma_t(\vec{r}, E)\phi = \\
\int_0^\infty dE' \int_{4\pi} d\hat{\Omega}' \Sigma_s(\vec{r}, E'\rightarrow E, \hat{\Omega}'\rightarrow\hat{\Omega})\phi(\vec{r}, E', \hat{\Omega}', t) \\

· S(\vec{r}, E, \hat{\Omega}, t)
  $$

Where:

· $\Sigma_t$ = total macroscopic cross-section (cm⁻¹)
· $\Sigma_s$ = scattering kernel
· $S$ = source term from GCR interactions

2.2 Martian Neutron Source Term

The source function $S(E, \theta)$ at depth $x$ (g/cm²) in the atmosphere:

S(E, x, \theta) = \sum_{A} \int_{E_{\text{thr}}}^\infty J_A(E_0) \frac{d\sigma_A}{dE}(E_0 \rightarrow E) \exp\left[-\frac{x}{\lambda_A(E_0, \theta)}\right] dE_0

Where:

· $J_A(E_0)$ = GCR flux of nucleus A at top of atmosphere
· $\lambda_A$ = attenuation length (~120 g/cm² for protons in CO₂)
· $\theta$ = zenith angle

2.3 Dose Conversion Algorithms

Dose equivalent $H$ is computed from neutron fluence $\Phi(E)$:

H = \int_0^\infty \Phi(E) \cdot h(E) \cdot RBE(E) \cdot Q(E) \ dE

Where:

· $h(E)$ = ICRP 116 fluence-to-dose conversion coefficients
· $RBE(E)$ = Quality factor from ICRP 60 (maximum 20 at 1 MeV)
· $Q(E)$ = Correction for Martian tissue depth (5-30 cm)

Implementation: Pre-computed matrices stored in FPGA, updated quarterly with latest ICRP recommendations.

2.4 Pulse-Shape Discrimination Mathematics

For organic scintillators (stilbene), neutron/gamma separation uses:

PSD = \frac{Q_{\text{tail}}}{Q_{\text{total}}}

Where $Q$ = integrated charge. The figure of merit:

FOM = \frac{|\mu_n - \mu_\gamma|}{\text{FWHM}_n + \text{FWHM}_\gamma}

Requirement: FOM > 1.2 for 99% separation efficiency at Martian background rates.

