SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE

3.0 DETECTOR PHYSICS & HARDWARE

3.1 Multi-Detector Core Specifications

3.1.1 He-3 Proportional Counters (4 units)

· Reaction: $^3\text{He} + n \rightarrow p + ^3\text{H} + 764\ \text{keV}$
· Cross-section: $\sigma_{\text{th}} = 5330\ \text{barn}$ at 0.0253 eV
· Gas: 4 atm $^3$He, 1 atm Kr quench gas
· Efficiency: 80% at thermal, <0.1% above 100 keV
· Dead time: 2 µs, paralyzable model

3.1.2 Stilbene Scintillator (Primary Fast Neutron)

· Dimensions: 5 cm diameter × 5 cm cylinder
· Light yield: 10,400 photons/MeVee
· Decay constants: $\tau_{\text{fast}} = 4.5\ \text{ns}$, $\tau_{\text{slow}} = 270\ \text{ns}$
· PMT: Hamamatsu R13089-100, 12-stage, quantum efficiency 25% at 410 nm

3.1.3 BC-408 Plastic Scintillator (Backup)

· Dimensions: 10 cm × 10 cm × 5 cm
· Light yield: 10,000 photons/MeVee
· Decay time: 2.1 ns
· Attenuation length: 210 cm at 425 nm

3.2 Shadow Shield Design

3.2.1 Material Composition

10 cm borated HDPE with composition by weight:

· Polyethylene (C₂H₄): 95%
· Boron carbide (B₄C): 5% with 95% enriched $^{10}$B

Macroscopic cross-sections:

· $\Sigma_s$ (H, 1 MeV) = 1.5 cm⁻¹
· $\Sigma_a$ ($^{10}$B, thermal) = 380 cm⁻¹

3.2.2 MCNP6 Validation Results

Simulation: 10⁹ particles, Martian spectrum with albedo

Energy (MeV) Incident Flux (cm⁻²s⁻¹) Transmitted Flux Attenuation
1×10⁻⁹ 3.2 ± 0.1 0.08 ± 0.01 40×
1×10⁻⁶ 2.1 ± 0.1 0.31 ± 0.02 6.8×
1×10⁻³ 1.8 ± 0.1 0.54 ± 0.03 3.3×
1.0 1.5 ± 0.1 0.78 ± 0.04 1.9×
10.0 0.9 ± 0.05 0.63 ± 0.03 1.4×
100.0 0.3 ± 0.02 0.27 ± 0.02 1.1×

3.2.3 Regolith Augmentation System

· Skirt: 15 cm high, removable aluminum
· Backfill protocol: Sentry-1 deposits 20 cm local regolith (ρ = 1.8 g/cm³)
· Additional attenuation: 40% reduction in side-scattered neutrons
· Mass penalty: 5 kg per node for skirt mechanism

3.3 Enhanced Protection Systems

3.3.1 Whipple Shield Layer

· 2 mm titanium (Grade 5) outer skin
· Mass addition: 1.2 kg
· Micro-meteoroid protection: Up to 0.5 mm aluminum equivalent at 10 km/s

3.3.2 Dust Mitigation

· Positive pressure: 1 kPa N₂ with redundant regulators
· Magnetic fluid seals on all penetrations
· Electrostatic dust removal: 5 kV grid on external surfaces

4.0 NETWORK DEPLOYMENT ARCHITECTURE

4.1 Three-Tier Monitoring Grid

4.1.1 Tier 1: Environmental Baseline (CSPH Node)

· Location: 3m mast at Central Storage & Processing Hub
· Coordinates: Settlement geographic center (established by dual-frequency GPS)
· Function: Establish $Φ_0(E)$, the unshielded environmental flux
· Data products:
  1. Hourly averaged spectra: 256 energy bins, 0.01 eV to 100 MeV
  2. Directional flux: 8-sector rose (45° resolution)
  3. Albedo ratio: Upward/downward flux = 0.35 ± 0.05 (expected)

4.1.2 Tier 2: Habitat Performance (Dual-Node Pair)

Exterior Node:

· Mounting: Habitat roof, 2m above highest point
· Shielding factor calculation:
  SF(t) = \frac{\int \Phi_{\text{ext}}(E,t) \cdot h(E) \ dE}{\int \Phi_{\text{int}}(E,t) \cdot h(E) \ dE}
· Water Wall correlation: 
  \frac{dSF}{dW} = -0.15\ \text{cm}^{-1}
  
  Where $W$ = water column density (g/cm²)

Interior Node:

· Location: Habitat central corridor, 1.5m height
· Dose rate display: 10-second updates on all habitat screens
· Alert threshold: 0.5 µSv/h increase sustained > 5 minutes

4.1.3 Tier 3: Mobile Survey (Sentry-1 Mounted)

· Integration: Rover sensor mast, 1.5m above ground
· Hydrogen detection sensitivity:
  \Delta\Phi_{\text{thermal}} = \Phi_0 \cdot \left[1 - \exp\left(-\Sigma_a^{\text{H}} \cdot N_{\text{H}} \cdot d\right)\right]
  
  Where $N_{\text{H}}$ = hydrogen atom density, $d$ = detector depth
· Minimum detectable: 0.5% water equivalent hydrogen in top 50 cm

4.2 Node Physical Specifications

Parameter Specification Notes
Dimensions 40 × 30 × 30 cm Including shield
Mass 39.2 kg With whipple shield and skirt
Power (nominal) 14 W 22 W during calibration
Operating temperature -100°C to +50°C Heated enclosure maintains >-40°C
Data rate 5 kB/hour Compressed spectral data
Lifetime 10 Earth years Limited by He-3 depletion (T₁/₂ = 12.32 y)
Redundancy N+2 4 He-3 tubes (any 2 functional)

5.0 ELECTRONICS & SIGNAL PROCESSING

5.1 Front-End Electronics

5.1.1 Charge-Sensitive Preamplifiers

· Gain: 1 V/pC for scintillators, 10 mV/pC for He-3
· Noise: < 1000 e⁻ RMS at 0 pF
· Shaping time: 0.5 µs (He-3), 50 ns (scintillators)

5.1.2 FPGA Processing (Xilinx Kintex-7 XQ7K325T)
Algorithms implemented:

1. Pulse height analysis: 12-bit ADC at 100 MSPS
2. PSD calculation: 
   \text{PSD} = \frac{\int_{t_1}^{t_2} V(t)dt}{\int_{t_0}^{t_2} V(t)dt}
   
   $t_0$ = trigger, $t_1$ = 30 ns, $t_2$ = 300 ns
3. Pile-up rejection: Dead time correction using:
   \tau_{\text{eff}} = \tau \cdot \left(1 - \frac{N_{\text{rej}}}{N_{\text{tot}}}\right)

5.2 Calibration Systems

5.2.1 Cf-252 Source

· Activity: 3.7 × 10⁴ Bq (1 µCi)
· Spectrum: Fission spectrum with average energy 2.1 MeV
· Mechanism: Rotary shutter, fail-safe closed position
· Encapsulation: Tungsten carbide, requires 50N force to access

5.2.2 LED Gain Monitoring

· LED: 405 nm pulsed at 1 kHz
· Photodiode reference: Stable to 0.1%/°C
· Gain tracking equation:
  G(t) = G_0 \cdot \exp\left(-\frac{t}{\tau_{\text{PMT}}}\right) \cdot \left[1 + \alpha(T - T_0)\right]
  
  Where $\tau_{\text{PMT}}$ = 5 years, $\alpha$ = -0.3%/°C

5.2.3 Cross-Calibration Protocol
Monthly procedure:

1. Deploy Cf-252 source: 30 minutes
2. Measure peak position: $\text{Ch}_{\text{peak}} = 2048 \pm 20$ required
3. Calculate efficiency:
   \epsilon = \frac{N_{\text{meas}}}{N_{\text{expected}} \cdot \Omega \cdot t}
   
   Where $\Omega$ = solid angle (0.12 sr)

6.0 DATA & AI INTEGRATION

6.1 Digital Twin Integration Architecture

6.1.1 Real-Time Dose Engine

```
Algorithm: Adaptive Simpson Integration
Input: Φ(E) from 256 energy bins
Output: H(t) with uncertainty σ_H
Update rate: 1 Hz
Accuracy: <10% (95% confidence interval)
```

6.1.2 Predictive Radiation Model
\frac{d\Phi}{dt} = \alpha \cdot \Phi_{\text{GCR}} + \beta \cdot \Phi_{\text{SPE}}(t - \Delta t) + \gamma \cdot \Phi_{\text{albedo}}


Where:

· $\alpha$ = GCR modulation (27-day solar rotation)
· $\beta$ = SPE propagation delay (8.3-16.6 minutes from Sun)
· $\gamma$ = Soil moisture correlation (0.1-0.5)
· $\Delta t$ = Light travel time + plasma delay

6.1.3 Terrain-Aware Flux Correction
For each node at position $\vec{r}_i$:
\Phi_{\text{corr}}(\vec{r}_i, E) = \Phi_{\text{model}}(E) \cdot \prod_{j=1}^{N_{\text{obs}}} T(\vec{r}_i, \vec{r}_j, E)


Where $T$ = transmission through obstacle $j$ calculated via line-of-sight ray tracing through LIDAR terrain model.

6.2 Communication Protocol

6.2.1 Time-Sensitive Networking Implementation

· Standard: IEEE 802.1Qbv (Time-Aware Shaper)
· Cycle time: 1 ms
· Critical traffic: ORANGE/RED alerts (highest priority)
· Latency guarantee: < 100 µs end-to-end
· Bandwidth allocation:
  · Priority 0 (Critical): 30%
  · Priority 1 (Telemetry): 50%
  · Priority 2 (Maintenance): 20%

6.2.2 CCSDS Packet Format
Primary Header (16 bytes):

```
Bits 0-31:   Packet version (3), Type (1), Secondary header flag (1)
Bits 32-63:  APID (Application Process ID)
Bits 64-95:  Sequence flags (2), Packet count (14)
Bits 96-127: Packet length (16)
```

Science Data Packet (256 bytes):

· Timestamp: 8 bytes (TAI, nanoseconds)
· Energy bins: 128 × 2 bytes (256 channels)
· Status: 2 bytes (health bits)
· Checksum: 4 bytes (CRC-32)

6.3 Alert Response System

6.3.1 Multi-Variable Alert Logic
Alert condition requires $N_{\text{trig}}$ of $M_{\text{conditions}}$:

Condition Weight Threshold
Flux increase > 50% 1.0 5 minutes
Two non-collocated nodes agree 0.8 3 minutes
SPE warning from orbit 0.7 Confirmed
Spectral hardening > 20% 0.6 10 minutes
Mobile node confirmation 0.5 Within 500m

Alert triggered if: $\sum w_i \cdot C_i \geq 2.0$

6.3.2 Shield Hardening Protocol
Stage 1 (YELLOW/ORANGE):

· Water Wall fill: 0% → 90% (45 seconds)
· Emergency power: Habitat sectors → 80% capacity
· Crew: Personal dosimeters activated

Stage 2 (RED):

· Water Wall: 90% → 100% + 5% overpressure
· Interior movable shields: Deploy (tungsten polyethylene composite)
· Crew: Retreat to storm shelter (10 g/cm² equivalent)

Performance: Dose rate reduction factor:
RF = \exp\left(\frac{-d}{\lambda(E)}\right)


Where $d$ = 20 g/cm² H₂O, $\lambda$ = 100 g/cm² for 100 MeV neutrons

