VALIDATION & TESTING

11.0 GROUND TESTING PROGRAM

11.1 Neutron Beam Characterization

Facilities: NIST, PTB, LANSCE
Test matrix:

1. Thermal beam: 0.0253 eV, flux 10⁴ n/cm²/s
2. Monteenergetic: 144 keV, 565 keV, 1.2 MeV, 5 MeV
3. White spectrum: 1-20 MeV (WNR facility)

Acceptance criteria:

· Efficiency within ±5% of MCNP prediction
· PSD FOM > 1.2 at all energies
· Linearity within ±2% up to 10⁵ cps

11.2 Environmental Testing

Thermal vacuum:

· Cycles: -120°C to +60°C, 10⁻⁶ Torr
· Duration: 50 cycles (5× margin)

Dust chamber:

· Simulant: JSC Mars-1, < 20 µm
· Concentration: 1 g/m³ at 15 m/s
· Duration: 100 hours

Vibration:

· Level: 14.1 grms (qualification), 9.4 grms (acceptance)
· Axes: 3 orthogonal, 1 minute each

12.0 MARS-ANALOG DEPLOYMENT

12.1 High-Altitude Test Site

Location: Mauna Kea, HI (4200 m elevation)

· Atmospheric depth: 600 g/cm² (vs Mars 16 g/cm²)
· Neutron flux: 5× Mars equivalent
· Duration: 90 sols continuous operation

Test objectives:

1. Validate network communication under delay/disruption
2. Test autonomous maintenance with rover prototype
3. Calibrate terrain shadowing algorithms
4. Validate alert protocols with human crews

12.2 Data Comparison

Benchmark against:

1. MSL-RAD data (reprocessed)
2. INL neutron transport codes
3. ESA DRAMA tool predictions

Acceptance: All measurements within 20% of benchmark

